"""
MKT Christ-in-Every-Verse Commentary — Genesis chapters 20–23
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-genesis-20-23.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/genesis.json (verse inventory)
- data/translation/draft/mediating/genesis.json (MKT text)
- data/commentary/mkt-christ/genesis.json (existing; ch22v13 already present)

Key Christological decisions:
- Gen 22 (Akedah): the most Christologically dense chapter in Genesis. The NT connections
  are explicit and extensive:
  • John 3:16 echoes 22:2 ("his one and only Son" ← "your son, your only son, whom you love")
  • Rom 8:32 directly echoes 22:12/16 ("did not spare his own Son" ← "you have not withheld
    your son, your only son")
  • Heb 11:17-19 reads Isaac as a type of resurrection: "in a manner of speaking he did
    receive Isaac back from the dead"
  • The three-day journey (22:4) connects to the third-day resurrection pattern
  • Isaac carrying the wood (22:6) = Jesus carrying the cross (John 19:17) — the image is
    deliberate typology in the tradition, supported by the structural parallel
  • The ram substitute (22:13) = the substitutionary atonement; already present, skipped
  • "God himself will provide the lamb" (22:8) = John 1:29 ("the Lamb of God")
  • YHWH-Jireh (22:14) = divine provision of the substitute, fulfilled in Christ
- Gen 21: Isaac's birth is the supreme fulfillment-in-type of the promise; Paul uses it
  directly in Gal 4:22-31 (Hagar/Sarah allegory) and Rom 9:7-9 (promise-children).
  The expulsion of Hagar/Ishmael (21:9-21) is quoted by Paul in Gal 4:30.
- Gen 20: Abraham as prophet-intercessor (v7) connects to the prophetic and intercessory
  offices that Christ fulfills. The repeated wife-sister failure shows the covenant-bearer
  is not himself the solution; Christ is.
- Gen 23: Heb 11:13 quotes the "foreigner and stranger" language (23:4) as the paradigm
  of faith's pilgrim posture. The Machpelah purchase is faith's first foothold in the
  promised land — the type of the inheritance secured by Christ.
- v22:13 is already present in the output file; merge_comm will skip it safely.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NEW_DATA = {
"20": {
"1": "<p>Abraham moved to the Negev and settled in Gerar &#8212; this is the second wife-sister incident, echoing ch12 with Pharaoh and anticipating Isaac's repetition of the same pattern in 26:6&#8211;11. The triple repetition of the patriarchal failure reveals that the covenant-bearers are themselves fallible and cannot be their own saviors. They participate in the promise not by their righteousness but by divine protection. This is the canonical-context frame for why Christ must be a different kind of covenant-bearer: &#8220;For what the law was powerless to do because it was weakened by the flesh, God did by sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh&#8221; (Rom 8:3). The repeated patriarchal failures establish the need for the one who does not fail.</p>",
"2": "<p>Abraham said of Sarah, &#8220;She is my sister,&#8221; and Abimelech took her &#8212; Abraham's deception that endangers the covenant promise. Sarah must be preserved for Isaac's birth; yet Abraham's cowardice places her at risk. The irony &#8212; that the bearer of the covenant promise repeatedly imperils it through his own weakness &#8212; is the structure that makes the virgin birth theologically necessary: the Messiah cannot come through a human father whose decisions can compromise the lineage. Luke 1:34&#8211;35 presents Christ's conception as bypassing the ordinary patriarchal channel precisely because the covenant's fulfillment cannot depend on human male decision-making: &#8220;How will this be, since I am a virgin?&#8221; &#8220;The Holy Spirit will come on you.&#8221;</p>",
"3": "<p>God came to Abimelech in a dream: &#8220;You are as good as dead because of the woman you have taken; she is a married woman&#8221; &#8212; God's direct intervention to protect the covenant-promise bearer, even at the risk of Abimelech's life. The divine protection of the covenant promise overrides the consequences of Abraham's failure. The God who protects Sarah even when Abraham fails is the God who &#8220;guards the feet of his faithful servants&#8221; (1 Sam 2:9), who keeps the covenant even when the covenant people are faithless: &#8220;if we are faithless, he remains faithful, for he cannot disown himself&#8221; (2 Tim 2:13). God's intervention through a dream to a Gentile king also anticipates the dream-warnings of the Nativity (Matt 2:12: Magi warned in a dream).</p>",
"4": "<p>Abimelech had not gone near Sarah, so he said, &#8220;Lord, will you destroy an innocent nation?&#8221; &#8212; Abimelech's appeal to divine justice: will God punish the innocent for the actions of the deceiver? The question is one of theodicy that runs through the OT (Gen 18:23: Abraham's &#8220;Will you sweep away the righteous with the wicked?&#8221;) and is resolved in Christ: God does not destroy the innocent nation but destroys his innocent Son for the sake of the guilty: &#8220;For Christ also suffered once for sins, the righteous for the unrighteous, to bring you to God&#8221; (1 Pet 3:18). The innocent who suffers for the guilty is the Christological inversion of Abimelech's fear.</p>",
"5": "<p>&#8220;Did he not say to me, &#8216;She is my sister&#8217;&#8230; I have done this with a clear conscience and clean hands&#8221; &#8212; Abimelech's claim of moral innocence in the deception. The standard of &#8220;clean hands&#8221; (Ps 24:4: &#8220;The one who has clean hands and a pure heart&#8221; may ascend the LORD&#8217;s hill) is the requirement for standing before God. Christ is the only one who meets this standard: &#8220;This is the one who stood before God with genuinely clean hands and a pure heart because he &#8216;committed no sin, and no deceit was found in his mouth&#8217;&#8221; (1 Pet 2:22; cf. Ps 24). Abimelech's claim of clean hands is partial; Christ&#8217;s clean hands are the ground on which he can offer himself as the final sacrifice (Heb 9:14: &#8220;offered himself unblemished to God&#8221;).</p>",
"6": "<p>God said, &#8220;Yes, I know you did this with a clear conscience, and so I have kept you from sinning against me. That is why I did not let you touch her&#8221; &#8212; divine restraint of sin: God prevents Abimelech from sinning further. The God who can restrain sin without removing free will is the God who &#8220;is faithful; he will not let you be tempted beyond what you can bear&#8221; (1 Cor 10:13). Christ, as the one who &#8220;is able to keep you from stumbling&#8221; (Jude 24), fulfills this divine function of preserving those who would otherwise fall. The restraint of sin by divine intervention is also the role of the Holy Spirit who intercedes and keeps believers (John 17:15: &#8220;keep them from the evil one&#8221;).</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;Return the man's wife, for he is a prophet, and he will pray for you and you will live&#8221; &#8212; Abraham called a prophet for the first time in Scripture. The prophetic office is the first of the three messianic offices (prophet, priest, king) that Christ fulfills. Abraham's intercession for Abimelech is the prophetic-intercessory function that Christ carries to its ultimate expression: &#8220;he always lives to intercede for them&#8221; (Heb 7:25); &#8220;Christ Jesus who died &#8212; more than that, who was raised to life &#8212; is at the right hand of God and is also interceding for us&#8221; (Rom 8:34). The prophet who intercedes so that others may live is the type of the great Prophet-Intercessor who lives to make intercession.</p>",
"8": "<p>Early the next morning Abimelech summoned his officials and told them what had happened, and they were very much afraid &#8212; the fear of God that follows divine revelation. The right response to an encounter with the living God is fear: &#8220;The fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom&#8221; (Prov 9:10); the disciples are &#8220;terrified&#8221; at the divine voice on the Mount of Transfiguration (Matt 17:6). Abimelech's court, hearing about God's dream-warning, responds with the appropriate response of creaturely fear before the holy God. Christ's ministry consistently produces this two-way response: faith and fear (Luke 5:8: &#8220;Go away from me, Lord; I am a sinful man!&#8221;).</p>",
"9": "<p>Abimelech called Abraham in and said, &#8220;What have you done to us? How have I wronged you that you have brought such great guilt upon me and my kingdom?&#8221; &#8212; Abimelech's moral reproach to Abraham. The irony is that the covenant-bearer is being morally rebuked by a pagan king. This reversal &#8212; the outsider seeing more clearly than the insider &#8212; is a pattern Christ employs: the faith of the centurion (Matt 8:10: &#8220;Truly I tell you, I have not found anyone in Israel with such great faith&#8221;), the compassion of the Good Samaritan, the gratitude of the Samaritan leper (Luke 17:16). The covenant people do not hold a monopoly on moral clarity; Christ extends his work beyond the expected boundaries.</p>",
"10": "<p>Abimelech asked Abraham, &#8220;What was your reason for doing this?&#8221; &#8212; the direct question demanding accountability for the deception. The pattern of accountability before God &#8212; &#8220;what have you done?&#8221; (Gen 3:13; 4:10) &#8212; runs through Genesis as a recurring divine and human moral inquiry. Christ's ministry involves the same confrontational questions: &#8220;Why are you thinking these things in your hearts?&#8221; (Mark 2:8). The accountability-question that exposes hidden motivation will reach its climax at the final judgment when &#8220;God will bring every deed into judgment, including every hidden thing, whether it is good or evil&#8221; (Eccl 12:14).</p>",
"11": "<p>Abraham replied, &#8220;I said to myself, &#8216;There is surely no fear of God in this place, and they will kill me because of my wife&#8217;&#8221; &#8212; Abraham's rationalization: he assumed the worst of Abimelech's court and acted on fear rather than faith. The assumption that &#8220;there is no fear of God in this place&#8221; turned out to be wrong &#8212; Abimelech's court was afraid (v8). Christ corrects the same assumption when disciples expect hostility: &#8220;Do not be afraid of them&#8221; (Matt 10:26); &#8220;In this world you will have trouble. But take heart! I have overcome the world&#8221; (John 16:33). Fear-driven decisions are consistently shown in the NT to be failures of faith in God's protective presence.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;Besides, she really is my sister, the daughter of my father though not of my mother; and she became my wife&#8221; &#8212; the technical accuracy of Abraham's partial truth. The distinction between a half-truth that deceives and the full truth that liberates is the frame for Christ's claim: &#8220;the truth will set you free&#8221; (John 8:32). Christ is &#8220;full of grace and truth&#8221; (John 1:14) &#8212; not partial truth strategically deployed to protect himself, but the full truth that costs him his life. The contrast between Abraham's truth-management and Christ's complete truthfulness is one marker of the type's inadequacy and the antitype's perfection.</p>",
"13": "<p>&#8220;And when God had me wander from my father's household, I said to her: &#8216;This is how you can show your love to me: Everywhere we go, say of me, &#8220;He is my brother.&#8221;&#8217;&#8221; &#8212; Abraham reveals the pre-arranged agreement: the deception is a standing policy, not a situational response. The pre-arranged compromise of truth for the sake of self-protection is the antithesis of Christ's consistent self-disclosure even when it cost him his life. Jesus does not hide his identity before the high priest even when the honest answer will condemn him: &#8220;You have said so&#8221; (Matt 26:64). Where Abraham pre-arranged his denial, Christ went to his death without denial.</p>",
"14": "<p>Abimelech brought sheep and cattle and male and female slaves and gave them to Abraham, returning Sarah &#8212; the restoration of what was endangered, with additional compensation. The generous restoration by a pagan king who was wronged by the covenant-bearer is a type of the grace that flows even from God's dealings through broken instruments. Paul notes that God uses even weak and foolish things to accomplish his purposes (1 Cor 1:27&#8211;28). The covenant promise is not derailed by Abraham's failure; God's purposes run through and despite human weakness &#8212; ultimately culminating in the one who does not fail (Heb 4:15: &#8220;tempted in every way, just as we are &#8212; yet he did not sin&#8221;).</p>",
"15": "<p>Abimelech said, &#8220;My land is before you; live wherever you like&#8221; &#8212; the open grant of Abimelech's territory to Abraham prefigures the worldwide scope of the land promise. The Gentile king granting access to his land anticipates the nations' eventual submission to Abraham's greater descendant: &#8220;Ask me, and I will make the nations your inheritance, the ends of the earth your possession&#8221; (Ps 2:8 &#8212; a psalm of the Davidic king applied to Christ). The land access granted by Abimelech is a local instance of the universal access to the inheritance that Christ secures for Abraham's offspring.</p>",
"16": "<p>To Sarah, Abimelech said, &#8220;I am giving your brother a thousand shekels of silver. This is to cover the offense against you before all who are with you&#8221; &#8212; the silver payment as public vindication of Sarah's honor. The covering of offense through payment anticipates the atonement's logic: sin brings public dishonor; atonement covers the offense publicly and completely. Christ's atonement is not a private arrangement but a public declaration: &#8220;God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement, through the shedding of his blood &#8212; to be received by faith. He did this to demonstrate his righteousness&#8221; (Rom 3:25). The public vindication of Sarah through payment is a type of the public vindication of sinners through Christ's blood.</p>",
"17": "<p>Abraham prayed to God, and God healed Abimelech, his wife, and his female slaves so they could have children again &#8212; Abraham's prophetic intercession results in healing. The prophet who prays and healing follows is the pattern of Elijah (1 Kgs 17:22), Elisha (2 Kgs 4:35), and Isaiah (2 Kgs 20:5). Christ heals directly and without prayer to another: &#8220;Jesus reached out his hand and touched the man. &#8216;I am willing,&#8217; he said. &#8216;Be healed!&#8217;&#8221; (Matt 8:3). The healings flow from his own authority (Matt 8:9: &#8220;I say to this one, &#8216;Go,&#8217; and he goes&#8221;), not from prophetic intercession. Abraham's intercessory healing is the type; Christ's direct healing reveals the healer-behind-the-type.</p>",
"18": "<p>The LORD had kept all the women in Abimelech's household from conceiving because of Abraham's wife Sarah &#8212; the divine closure of wombs is a recurring narrative device (Rachel, 29:31; Hannah, 1 Sam 1:5-6) that emphasizes that human conception is ultimately in God's hands. The God who opens and closes wombs according to his covenant purposes is the same God who opens Sarah's womb at 90 (21:1&#8211;2) and who causes the virgin to conceive (Luke 1:35). The barrenness and fruitfulness of wombs throughout Genesis is the biological pattern behind the theological truth: &#8220;children born not of natural descent, nor of human decision or a husband's will, but born of God&#8221; (John 1:13).</p>",
},
"21": {
"1": "<p>The LORD was gracious to Sarah as he had said, and the LORD did for Sarah what he had promised &#8212; the chapter opens with a double statement of fulfillment: &#8220;as he had said&#8221; and &#8220;what he had promised.&#8221; The divine promise-keeping that has seemed so long delayed is now enacted. Paul makes this the model for gospel faith: &#8220;No matter how many promises God has made, they are &#8216;Yes&#8217; in Christ. And so through him the &#8216;Amen&#8217; is spoken by us to the glory of God&#8221; (2 Cor 1:20). The yes of God to Sarah&#8217;s barren womb is the prototype of the ultimate yes that God speaks to all his promises in the person and work of Christ.</p>",
"2": "<p>Sarah became pregnant and bore a son to Abraham in his old age, at the very time God had promised him &#8212; &#8220;at the very time God had promised&#8221; is the key phrase: the birth occurs on the divine timetable, not the human one. Paul uses this same temporal precision for Christ&#8217;s coming: &#8220;when the set time had fully come, God sent his Son, born of a woman, born under the law&#8221; (Gal 4:4). The &#8220;set time&#8221; (plēroma tou chronou) of the incarnation corresponds to &#8220;the very time God had promised&#8221; for Isaac&#8217;s birth. Divine faithfulness operates on a timetable that human impatience cannot accelerate; the wait for the promise is itself part of the covenant pedagogy.</p>",
"3": "<p>Abraham gave the name Isaac to the son Sarah bore him &#8212; Isaac means &#8220;he laughs&#8221; or &#8220;laughter&#8221; (see v6). The naming of the child of promise is an act of covenant recognition: this is the son through whom the promise runs. Paul reads Isaac as the type of believers who are &#8220;children of promise&#8221; (Gal 4:28: &#8220;Now you, brothers and sisters, like Isaac, are children of promise&#8221;). The child of promise who is named and recognized is the type of the one who names the covenant children: &#8220;I will acknowledge their name before my Father and his angels&#8221; (Rev 3:5). Christ names and acknowledges those who are his through the promised Spirit.</p>",
"4": "<p>Abraham circumcised Isaac when his son was eight days old, as God had commanded him &#8212; the covenant sign applied to the child of promise on the eighth day. The eighth-day circumcision (Lev 12:3; Phil 3:5: &#8220;circumcised on the eighth day&#8221;) marks membership in the covenant community. Christ is circumcised on the eighth day (Luke 2:21: &#8220;when the time came for them to be circumcised according to the law&#8221;), entering the covenant community he came to fulfill. Paul in Col 2:11&#8211;12 connects circumcision to baptism: &#8220;In him you were also circumcised with a circumcision not performed by human hands&#8230; having been buried with him in baptism.&#8221; The eighth-day covenant sign is fulfilled in Christ&#8217;s own submission to it and in the new-covenant circumcision of the heart.</p>",
"5": "<p>Abraham was a hundred years old when his son Isaac was born &#8212; the chronological marker that emphasizes the impossibility of the birth by natural means. Paul uses this explicitly in Romans 4: &#8220;Without weakening in his faith, he faced the fact that his body was as good as dead &#8212; since he was about a hundred years old &#8212; and that Sarah&#8217;s womb was also dead. Yet he did not waver through unbelief&#8221; (Rom 4:19&#8211;20). The hundred-year-old father and the ninety-year-old mother are the impossibility that faith transcends. Christ&#8217;s resurrection is the ultimate impossibility that faith embraces: &#8220;God who gives life to the dead and calls into being things that were not&#8221; (Rom 4:17) &#8212; the same God who gave life to Sarah&#8217;s dead womb raises Christ from the dead.</p>",
"6": "<p>Sarah said, &#8220;God has brought me laughter, and everyone who hears about this will laugh with me&#8221; &#8212; the laughter of fulfilled promise. Sarah laughed in disbelief when the promise was announced (18:12); she laughs in joy when it is fulfilled. The transformation of incredulous laughter to joyful laughter is the pattern of the gospel&#8217;s reception: the news of the resurrection is met with disbelief (Matt 28:17: &#8220;some doubted&#8221;), but those who receive it enter the joy of fulfilled promise: &#8220;Though you have not seen him, you love him; and even though you do not see him now, you believe in him and are filled with an inexpressible and glorious joy&#8221; (1 Pet 1:8). The laughter at Isaac&#8217;s birth prefigures the eschatological joy at the resurrection.</p>",
"7": "<p>&#8220;Who would have said to Abraham that Sarah would nurse children? Yet I have borne him a son in his old age&#8221; &#8212; the wonderment at the impossible fulfilled. The &#8220;who would have said&#8221; is the OT pattern of amazement at divine action that exceeds human expectation: &#8220;Who has believed our message and to whom has the arm of the LORD been revealed?&#8221; (Isa 53:1). The gospel&#8217;s announcement of a crucified Messiah is similarly &#8220;a stumbling block to Jews and foolishness to Gentiles&#8221; (1 Cor 1:23) until it is received as the power and wisdom of God. Sarah&#8217;s amazement at the impossible birth is the prototype of the apostolic amazement at the resurrection.</p>",
"8": "<p>The child grew and was weaned, and Abraham held a great feast on the day Isaac was weaned &#8212; the feast celebrating the weaned child&#8217;s growing independence is a type of the eschatological feast that Christ will host. Jesus himself uses feasting as the primary image for the kingdom: &#8220;the kingdom of heaven is like a king who prepared a wedding banquet for his son&#8221; (Matt 22:2); &#8220;Many will come from east and west and recline at table with Abraham, Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven&#8221; (Matt 8:11). The feast at Isaac&#8217;s weaning is the first of several covenant feasts in the patriarchal narratives; the eschatological feast with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob is the fulfillment that Christ announces.</p>",
"9": "<p>Sarah saw the son of Hagar the Egyptian mocking &#8212; the conflict between the two sons that Paul interprets as the conflict between the two covenants. Gal 4:29: &#8220;at that time the son born according to the flesh persecuted the son born by the Spirit.&#8221; Paul applies this dynamic to his own situation: those who insist on circumcision and the law &#8220;persecute&#8221; those who live by faith in the promise. The mocking of the child of promise by the child of human arrangement is the historical type of the law&#8217;s burden on those who seek to live by faith. Christ frees believers from this burden: &#8220;It is for freedom that Christ has set us free. Stand firm, then, and do not let yourselves be burdened again by a yoke of slavery&#8221; (Gal 5:1).</p>",
"10": "<p>Sarah said, &#8220;Get rid of that slave woman and her son, for that woman's son will never share in the inheritance with my son Isaac&#8221; &#8212; Paul quotes this verse directly in Gal 4:30: &#8220;Get rid of the slave woman and her son, for the slave woman's son will never share in the inheritance with the free woman's son.&#8221; Paul applies it to the incompatibility of law-righteousness and faith-righteousness as paths to the inheritance. The inheritance &#8212; justification before God, eternal life, the new creation &#8212; comes exclusively through the promise-line (through Christ) and not through the human-effort line (through the law). The two cannot coexist as parallel paths to the inheritance.</p>",
"11": "<p>The matter distressed Abraham greatly because it concerned his son &#8212; the pain of separating from Ishmael. The divine commands that are painful to obey are the tests of covenant loyalty; the Akedah (ch22) will push this further. Abraham&#8217;s grief over Ishmael anticipates the grief of the Father who &#8220;did not spare his own Son&#8221; (Rom 8:32). The paternal love that must nonetheless yield to the divine command is the typological structure of the Akedah. Here it is the sending away of Ishmael; in ch22 it is the offering of Isaac; in the NT it is the giving of the Son. The sequence of paternal sacrifices deepens toward the cross.</p>",
"12": "<p>God said to Abraham, &#8220;Do not be so distressed about the boy and your slave woman. Listen to whatever Sarah tells you, because it is through Isaac that your offspring will be reckoned&#8221; &#8212; the divine narrowing of the covenant promise to the Isaac line is confirmed. Paul quotes the end of this verse in Rom 9:7: &#8220;Not all who are descended from Israel are Israel&#8230; it is through Isaac that your offspring will be reckoned.&#8221; Paul uses it to establish that physical descent from Abraham does not constitute covenant membership; the covenant runs through the promise-line (Isaac) and ultimately through the one seed who is Christ (Gal 3:16). The divine declaration &#8220;it is through Isaac&#8221; becomes &#8220;it is through Christ&#8221; in the NT&#8217;s reading of the covenant.</p>",
"13": "<p>&#8220;I will make the son of the slave woman into a nation also, because he is your offspring&#8221; &#8212; God&#8217;s care for Ishmael and the non-covenant line. The divine promise to Ishmael (also 16:10&#8211;11) shows that those outside the specific covenant line are not outside God&#8217;s general care and providence. Paul&#8217;s anguish for Israel in Rom 9:1&#8211;5 reflects the same theological tension: those who are outside the current covenant-fulfillment (Israel not yet believing in Christ) are still loved and within God&#8217;s larger purposes (Rom 11:25&#8211;26: &#8220;all Israel will be saved&#8221;). Christ&#8217;s mission includes the &#8220;other sheep&#8221; (John 10:16: &#8220;I have other sheep that are not of this sheep pen&#8221;) &#8212; the Ishmael-line nations that are not the primary covenant line but are within the scope of God&#8217;s concern.</p>",
"14": "<p>Early next morning Abraham took food and a skin of water and gave them to Hagar, setting them on her shoulders and sending her off with the boy &#8212; the sending away of Hagar and Ishmael mirrors the Exodus (Exod 12:39: Israel set out in haste) and anticipates the exile. Those who are sent away by the covenant community are not beyond God&#8217;s reach: vv17&#8211;20 show God finding and providing for Hagar and Ishmael in the desert. Christ seeks the lost and the expelled: &#8220;the Son of Man came to seek and to save the lost&#8221; (Luke 19:10); &#8220;he saw a great crowd, and he had compassion on them, because they were like sheep without a shepherd&#8221; (Matt 9:36). The God who sends and the God who seeks are not in contradiction.</p>",
"15": "<p>When the water in the skin was gone, Hagar put the boy under one of the bushes &#8212; the extremity of thirst and near-death. The water-to-thirst-to-divine-provision pattern runs through the wilderness narratives (Exod 15:22&#8211;25; 17:1&#8211;7) and reaches its fulfillment in Christ who offers living water that permanently quenches spiritual thirst: &#8220;Whoever drinks the water I give them will never thirst. Indeed, the water I give them will become in them a spring of water welling up to eternal life&#8221; (John 4:14). The water that runs out in the desert is the type of all earthly provision that eventually fails; Christ is the provision that does not run out.</p>",
"16": "<p>Hagar sat at a distance, weeping, unable to watch the boy die &#8212; the grief of a mother who cannot save her dying child. The maternal grief at the death of a child reaches its depth in the NT at the cross: Mary stands watching her son die (John 19:25&#8211;27). Where Hagar cannot save Ishmael and weeps in helplessness, God hears the boy&#8217;s cry (v17). Where Mary cannot save Jesus, God raises him on the third day. In both cases, the human mother can only witness; divine intervention alone brings rescue and life. The weeping mother&#8217;s helplessness is the foil that reveals God as the sole source of life.</p>",
"17": "<p>God heard the boy crying, and the angel of God called to Hagar from heaven: &#8220;What is the matter, Hagar? Do not be afraid; God has heard the boy crying&#8221; &#8212; the angel of God (here; the &#8220;angel of the LORD&#8221; in ch16) calls from heaven to answer the cry of the dying. &#8220;Do not be afraid&#8221; is the recurring divine assurance at every moment of divine appearance. The God who hears the boy&#8217;s cry answers through the angelic messenger, demonstrating the divine attentiveness to those outside the primary covenant line. Christ&#8217;s healing ministry similarly extends to those outside the expected circle: the Syrophoenician woman&#8217;s daughter (Mark 7:24&#8211;30), the Samaritan leper (Luke 17:16), the centurion&#8217;s servant (Matt 8:5&#8211;13). &#8220;Everyone who calls on the name of the Lord will be saved&#8221; (Rom 10:13) &#8212; including Ishmael&#8217;s line.</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;Lift the boy up and take him by the hand, for I will make him into a great nation&#8221; &#8212; the divine lifting of the fallen and the promise of greatness through the one who was nearly lost. The &#8220;lifting up&#8221; of the dying boy connects to the resurrection pattern: &#8220;lifted up from the ground&#8221; (John 12:32, where Jesus speaks of being &#8220;lifted up&#8221; on the cross and drawing all people to himself). The promise &#8220;I will make him into a great nation&#8221; &#8212; even Ishmael, even the expelled, even the nearly dead &#8212; is the grace that extends beyond the narrow covenant channel, anticipating the gospel&#8217;s reach to all nations through Christ.</p>",
"19": "<p>God opened her eyes and she saw a well of water &#8212; the divine opening of eyes to see what was already there. The well was present in the desert; Hagar simply could not see it. The pattern of eyes opened to see what was previously invisible is a recurring gospel motif: the disciples&#8217; eyes opened to recognize the risen Christ (Luke 24:31: &#8220;Then their eyes were opened and they recognized him&#8221;); the blind receiving sight (John 9); Elisha&#8217;s servant&#8217;s eyes opened to see the heavenly army (2 Kgs 6:17). Christ opens eyes &#8212; physically in his miracles, spiritually through the Spirit &#8212; to see the provision and the presence that were always there but invisible to the natural eye.</p>",
"20": "<p>God was with the boy as he grew up. He lived in the desert and became an archer &#8212; the divine presence with Ishmael outside the covenant community is a type of God&#8217;s general providence with all people. Matt 5:45: &#8220;He causes his sun to rise on the evil and the good, and sends rain on the righteous and the unrighteous.&#8221; God&#8217;s common grace accompanies Ishmael&#8217;s desert life; this is not saving grace (which comes through the covenant-promise line that culminates in Christ) but the sustaining providence that keeps all people alive and capable of the dignity that God&#8217;s image requires (Acts 17:28: &#8220;in him we live and move and have our being&#8221;).</p>",
"21": "<p>While living in the Desert of Paran, his mother got a wife for him from Egypt &#8212; Ishmael&#8217;s settlement in Paran and marriage to an Egyptian connects him to the region between Sinai and Canaan, the territory through which Israel will later journey in the Exodus. The Egyptian wife continues the Hagar-Egyptian lineage. This is a canonical-context note: Ishmael&#8217;s descendants settle in the region that becomes the background for the Exodus, which itself becomes the type of Christ&#8217;s redemption. The geographic situating of Ishmael&#8217;s line is part of the broader mapping of peoples that the table of nations (ch10) and subsequent genealogies provide.</p>",
"22": "<p>Abimelech and Phicol said to Abraham, &#8220;God is with you in everything you do&#8221; &#8212; the Gentile recognition of the divine presence with the covenant-bearer. The pagan leaders see in Abraham what Israel&#8217;s neighbors will later see in Joseph (39:3: &#8220;His master saw that the LORD was with him&#8221;), Daniel (Dan 6:23), and ultimately in Christ himself: &#8220;No one could perform the signs you are doing if God were not with him&#8221; (John 3:2). The divine presence recognized by outsiders is the canonical testimony to the covenant-bearer&#8217;s legitimacy. Christ is Emmanuel, &#8220;God with us&#8221; (Matt 1:23) &#8212; the one in whom divine presence is not an observable quality but the literal truth.</p>",
"23": "<p>Abimelech asked Abraham to swear not to deal falsely with him or his descendants &#8212; a covenant of non-aggression between the covenant-bearer and the surrounding peoples. The covenant that extends to &#8220;my children and my descendants&#8221; is the multi-generational scope of covenant commitment. Christ establishes a new covenant that also reaches across generations: &#8220;The promise is for you and your children and for all who are far off &#8212; for all whom the Lord our God will call&#8221; (Acts 2:39). The covenant of mutual faithfulness between Abraham and Abimelech is the horizontal-covenant pattern of which the new covenant between God and humanity through Christ is the vertical fulfillment.</p>",
"24": "<p>Abraham said, &#8220;I swear it&#8221; &#8212; the covenant oath. The covenant sealed by an oath is the pattern that Hebrews applies to both the Abrahamic covenant and Christ&#8217;s high priesthood: &#8220;Others became priests without any oath, but he became a priest with an oath when God said to him: &#8216;The Lord has sworn and will not change his mind: &#8220;You are a priest forever.&#8221;&#8217;&#8221; (Heb 7:20&#8211;21). The oath that ratifies the covenant is the divine guarantee of its permanence. Abraham&#8217;s &#8220;I swear it&#8221; to Abimelech is the human covenant-oath pattern; God&#8217;s oath to make Christ a priest forever is the divine covenant-oath that secures the new covenant beyond all contingency.</p>",
"25": "<p>Abraham complained to Abimelech about a well of water that Abimelech's servants had seized &#8212; the well-dispute that leads to the Beer-sheba covenant. The well is a site of both conflict and resolution throughout the patriarchal narratives (Isaac&#8217;s wells in 26:19&#8211;22; Jacob&#8217;s well in John 4). Wells are life-sources in the desert; their ownership is worth contesting. Christ at Jacob&#8217;s well (John 4:7&#8211;14) transforms the territorial water-dispute into an offer of living water that transcends all territorial claims: &#8220;the water I give them will become in them a spring of water welling up to eternal life&#8221; &#8212; water no one can seize or dispute.</p>",
"26": "<p>Abimelech said, &#8220;I don't know who did this&#8221; &#8212; the covenant partner&#8217;s denial of knowledge of the injustice. The inability of covenant partners to guarantee justice even when they intend it is a recurring limitation of human covenants. Human covenants fail because humans are limited in knowledge and power. Christ as the covenant mediator of the new covenant (Heb 9:15) is not limited in this way: &#8220;Nothing in all creation is hidden from God&#8217;s sight&#8221; (Heb 4:13). The new covenant&#8217;s security rests on the mediator who knows all things and whose power to enforce and fulfill is unlimited.</p>",
"27": "<p>Abraham brought sheep and cattle and gave them to Abimelech, and the two men made a treaty &#8212; the covenant ratified by gift and by mutual recognition. The covenant gifts of animals prefigure the sacrificial system that ratifies Israel&#8217;s covenant at Sinai (Exod 24:5&#8211;8). The new covenant is ratified by the ultimate gift &#8212; not sheep and cattle but the blood of Christ (Heb 9:12: &#8220;he entered the Most Holy Place once for all by his own blood, thus obtaining eternal redemption&#8221;; Heb 10:4: &#8220;it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins&#8221;). The animal covenant-gifts of the patriarchal era are the shadow; Christ&#8217;s blood is the substance.</p>",
"28": "<p>Abraham set apart seven ewe lambs from the flock &#8212; the seven lambs set apart for the covenant witness at Beer-sheba. Seven is the covenant-completion number in OT ritual (seven days, seven times, seven animals). The setting apart of seven lambs to testify to the well&#8217;s ownership is a type of the covenant sign and seal; the Lord&#8217;s Supper is the new covenant&#8217;s sign, set apart as testimony to Christ&#8217;s once-for-all sacrifice (1 Cor 11:26: &#8220;whenever you eat this bread and drink this cup, you proclaim the Lord&#8217;s death until he comes&#8221;). The seven lambs are separated from the flock; Christ is the one lamb set apart from eternity (1 Pet 1:20: &#8220;chosen before the creation of the world&#8221;).</p>",
"29": "<p>Abimelech asked, &#8220;What is the meaning of these seven ewe lambs you have set apart by themselves?&#8221; &#8212; the question about the meaning of the covenant sign. The pattern of covenant sign plus question-and-answer runs through the OT ritual system: Passover (Exod 12:26&#8211;27: &#8220;when your children ask&#8230; tell them&#8221;), the stones at the Jordan (Josh 4:6&#8211;7), the Lord&#8217;s Supper (1 Cor 11:26: &#8220;you proclaim the Lord&#8217;s death until he comes&#8221;). Every covenant sign is established to prompt inquiry and instruction. The seven lambs here are explained (v30); the Lord&#8217;s Supper is explained by Christ himself (Matt 26:26&#8211;28: &#8220;This is my body&#8230; This is my blood of the covenant&#8221;).</p>",
"30": "<p>Abraham replied, &#8220;Accept these seven lambs from my hand as a witness that I dug this well&#8221; &#8212; the seven lambs as legal testimony establishing ownership. The witness-function of the covenant sign &#8212; providing evidence for a claim that cannot otherwise be proven &#8212; is the function that the Holy Spirit fulfills in the new covenant: &#8220;The Spirit himself testifies with our spirit that we are God&#8217;s children&#8221; (Rom 8:16). The Spirit is the covenant witness who establishes the believer&#8217;s inheritance in Christ: &#8220;you were marked in him with a seal, the promised Holy Spirit, who is a deposit guaranteeing our inheritance&#8221; (Eph 1:13&#8211;14). The seven lambs as legal witness are the OT type of the Spirit as covenant witness.</p>",
"31": "<p>That place was called Beersheba because the two men swore an oath there &#8212; Beer-sheba, &#8220;well of the oath&#8221; or &#8220;well of seven.&#8221; The naming of the place commemorates the covenant event. Place-naming as covenant commemoration runs through Genesis (Bethel, Peniel, Beer Lahai Roi) and reaches its fulfillment in the new name given to believers: &#8220;I will write on them the name of my God and the name of the city of my God, the new Jerusalem&#8230; and I will also write on them my new name&#8221; (Rev 3:12). The name that commemorates the covenant encounter is the type of the new name in Christ that marks permanent belonging.</p>",
"32": "<p>After the covenant was made at Beersheba, Abimelech and Phicol returned to the land of the Philistines &#8212; the covenant concluded, the parties return to their territories. The covenant of peace between Abraham and Abimelech is a type of the peace that Christ establishes: &#8220;For he himself is our peace, who has made the two groups one and has destroyed the barrier, the dividing wall of hostility&#8221; (Eph 2:14). The covenants between Abraham and his Gentile neighbors anticipate the larger reconciliation of Jew and Gentile that Christ accomplishes in his body.</p>",
"33": "<p>Abraham planted a tamarisk tree in Beersheba, and there he called on the name of the LORD, the Eternal God (El Olam) &#8212; the tamarisk tree as a living covenant monument, and the naming of God as &#8220;the Eternal God.&#8221; El Olam (the Everlasting God) is used here for the first time. Christ is the embodiment of El Olam&#8217;s eternality: &#8220;Jesus Christ is the same yesterday and today and forever&#8221; (Heb 13:8); &#8220;In the beginning was the Word, and the Word was with God, and the Word was God&#8221; (John 1:1). The tree planted at the covenant site is the living symbol of covenantal permanence; the cross, planted in the ground of Golgotha, is the permanent covenant monument of the new creation.</p>",
"34": "<p>Abraham stayed in the land of the Philistines for a long time &#8212; the patience of living peaceably in territory that is not yet fully the covenant possession. The pilgrim existence of Abraham in the Philistines&#8217; land &#8212; a sojourner among peoples who are not his covenant community &#8212; is the posture that Hebrews 11:13 holds up as the model of faith: &#8220;they admitted that they were foreigners and strangers on earth.&#8221; Christ&#8217;s disciples live the same pilgrim existence: &#8220;our citizenship is in heaven&#8221; (Phil 3:20); &#8220;you are foreigners and exiles&#8221; (1 Pet 2:11). The long sojourn in the Philistines&#8217; land is the type of the church&#8217;s long sojourn in the world while awaiting the full inheritance.</p>",
},
"22": {
"1": "<p>God tested Abraham &#8212; the testing (nasah) is the theological frame that the narrator places explicitly before the event. This is not entrapment but covenant-refining: &#8220;when I have tested him, he will come forth as gold&#8221; (Job 23:10; cf. 1 Pet 1:7: &#8220;your faith &#8212; of greater worth than gold, which perishes even though refined by fire&#8221;). Christ himself is tested in the wilderness (Matt 4:1: &#8220;Jesus was led by the Spirit into the wilderness to be tempted by the devil&#8221;) and in Gethsemane (Matt 26:36&#8211;46). The divine testing of the covenant-bearer is not divine cruelty but the means by which the faithfulness of the tested is revealed and confirmed.</p>",
"2": "<p>&#8220;Take your son, your only son, whom you love &#8212; Isaac &#8212; and go to the region of Moriah. Sacrifice him there as a burnt offering&#8221; &#8212; the triple intensification of the command (&#8220;your son, your only son, whom you love&#8221;) is the verbal texture that John 3:16 echoes: &#8220;For God so loved the world that he gave his one and only Son.&#8221; The language of God&#8217;s command to Abraham is the language John uses for God&#8217;s own giving of Christ. The father who loves his son but is commanded to give him is the human type of the Father who loves the Son and gives him for the world&#8217;s salvation. Moriah is identified in 2 Chron 3:1 as the site of Solomon&#8217;s temple in Jerusalem &#8212; the mountain where the ultimate sacrifice is eventually offered.</p>",
"3": "<p>Early next morning Abraham got up and loaded his donkey, took two servants and his son Isaac, cut the wood, and set out &#8212; Abraham&#8217;s prompt obedience without visible hesitation. The early morning rising mirrors the early morning entry of the crucifixion narrative (Mark 15:1: &#8220;Very early in the morning, the chief priests&#8230; reached a decision&#8221;). The prompt, unflinching movement toward the place of sacrifice despite its cost is the type of Christ&#8217;s &#8220;resolutely setting out for Jerusalem&#8221; (Luke 9:51: &#8220;As the time approached for him to be taken up to heaven, Jesus resolutely set out for Jerusalem&#8221;). Both the type and the antitype move toward the sacrifice with deliberate, early-morning determination.</p>",
"4": "<p>On the third day Abraham looked up and saw the place in the distance &#8212; the third-day arrival at the place of sacrifice. The three-day pattern is everywhere in Scripture: Jonah in the great fish three days (Matt 12:40: &#8220;For as Jonah was three days and three nights in the belly of a huge fish, so the Son of Man will be three days and three nights in the heart of the earth&#8221;); Israel at Sinai to prepare for God&#8217;s appearance (Exod 19:11, 15); Esther&#8217;s three-day fast before approaching the king. Heb 11:19 says Abraham reasoned that God could raise Isaac from the dead &#8212; &#8220;in a manner of speaking he did receive Isaac back from the dead&#8221; on the third day. The third-day arrival at Moriah is the type of the third-day resurrection.</p>",
"5": "<p>Abraham said to his servants, &#8220;Stay here with the donkey while I and the boy go over there. We will worship and then we will come back to you&#8221; &#8212; &#8220;We will come back&#8221; (plural): Abraham speaks in faith that both he and Isaac will return. Whether Abraham expects God to stop the sacrifice or to raise Isaac afterward, his faith in God&#8217;s power to fulfill the promise through Isaac (cf. Heb 11:17&#8211;19) is the ground of this plural. The plural &#8220;we&#8221; is the prophetic faith-statement that the disciples experience on Easter morning: Jesus says &#8220;I will go ahead of you into Galilee&#8221; (Matt 26:32) &#8212; the confidence that the sacrifice does not end in death but in return. Faith speaks of the return before the sacrifice.</p>",
"6": "<p>Abraham took the wood for the burnt offering and placed it on his son Isaac, and he himself carried the fire and the knife &#8212; Isaac carrying the wood for the burnt offering on which he will be offered. The image is one of the most striking types in the OT: the son carries the instrument of his own sacrifice to the place of offering. John 19:17: &#8220;Carrying his own cross, he went out to the place of the Skull (which in Aramaic is called Golgotha).&#8221; As Isaac carried the wood (= the cross), Jesus carried his cross. The wood that Isaac bears is the means of execution prepared for him; Christ carries the cross, the means of execution that was prepared for him. The correspondence is precise and deliberate in the typological tradition.</p>",
"7": "<p>Isaac spoke up: &#8220;Father?&#8221; &#8220;Yes, my son?&#8221; &#8220;The fire and wood are here, but where is the lamb for the burnt offering?&#8221; &#8212; Isaac&#8217;s question is the question that the entire sacrificial system asks. The lamb is always the central figure: Passover lamb, daily burnt offering lambs, Day of Atonement sacrifices, the servant of Isaiah 53:7 (&#8220;like a lamb led to the slaughter&#8221;). John 1:29: &#8220;Look, the Lamb of God, who takes away the sin of the world!&#8221; &#8212; John the Baptist&#8217;s cry is the answer to Isaac&#8217;s question. Where is the lamb? Every sacrifice pointed forward to the answer that arrives in Christ. &#8220;Where is the lamb?&#8221; is the OT&#8217;s deepest question; &#8220;Behold the Lamb of God&#8221; is the NT&#8217;s answer.</p>",
"8": "<p>Abraham answered, &#8220;God himself will provide the lamb for the burnt offering, my son&#8221; &#8212; the prophetic faith-statement that is both immediately true (the ram in v13) and ultimately true at a depth Abraham does not yet see. The statement &#8220;God himself will provide&#8221; is the theological center of the Akedah and the OT&#8217;s clearest prefiguration of the doctrine of substitutionary atonement: God does not require the sacrifice of human children; God provides the sacrifice himself. &#8220;He who did not spare his own Son, but gave him up for us all&#8221; (Rom 8:32) &#8212; God provides not a ram for Abraham but his own Son for sinners. The &#8220;God himself will provide&#8221; is the OT promise that the cross fulfills.</p>",
"9": "<p>Abraham built the altar, arranged the wood, bound his son Isaac, and laid him on the altar on top of the wood &#8212; the binding of Isaac (the &#8220;Akedah&#8221;) is the central image of the chapter. Isaac&#8217;s submission to being bound and placed on the altar is the type of Christ&#8217;s voluntary submission to the cross. &#8220;No one takes my life from me, but I lay it down of my own accord&#8221; (John 10:18). Both Isaac and Christ submit voluntarily &#8212; Isaac could likely have resisted his elderly father, but he does not; Christ &#8220;humbled himself by becoming obedient to death &#8212; even death on a cross&#8221; (Phil 2:8). The son&#8217;s willing submission to the father&#8217;s will is the typological heart of the Akedah.</p>",
"10": "<p>Abraham reached out his hand and took the knife to slay his son &#8212; the moment of maximum obedience, the nadir before the divine intervention. Hebrews 11:17 says Abraham &#8220;offered up Isaac&#8221; (perfect tense &#8212; the act was complete in his heart and intention before the ram was provided). The willingness to sacrifice the beloved son is the complete test of covenant loyalty; it is also the type of the Father&#8217;s willingness in the gospel: &#8220;God so loved the world that he gave&#8221; (John 3:16). The raised knife is the moment before which the type stops &#8212; God stops Abraham &#8212; because the substitution is provided. But the knife does not stop at Calvary; the Father does not spare the Son (Rom 8:32).</p>",
"11": "<p>The angel of the LORD called out from heaven, &#8220;Abraham! Abraham!&#8221; &#8220;Here I am&#8221; &#8212; the double-name call (&#8220;Abraham! Abraham!&#8221;) marks a moment of highest urgency and divine intensity: &#8220;Moses! Moses!&#8221; at the burning bush (Exod 3:4), &#8220;Samuel! Samuel!&#8221; at the divine call (1 Sam 3:10), &#8220;Simon, Simon!&#8221; before Peter&#8217;s denial (Luke 22:31), &#8220;Saul, Saul!&#8221; on the Damascus road (Acts 9:4). The doubled name signals a turning point in the divine-human relationship. The angel calling from heaven corresponds to the Father&#8217;s voice from heaven at Christ&#8217;s baptism (Matt 3:17) and transfiguration (Matt 17:5): the divine voice from heaven authenticating the covenant relationship at the critical moment.</p>",
"12": "<p>&#8220;Do not do anything to him. Now I know that you fear God, because you have not withheld from me your son, your only son&#8221; &#8212; the divine recognition of Abraham&#8217;s obedience. &#8220;You have not withheld&#8230; your son, your only son&#8221; &#8212; the same triple identification as v2, now turned into a statement of what Abraham has given. Paul uses this language for God&#8217;s action in Christ: &#8220;He who did not spare his own Son, but gave him up for us all&#8221; (Rom 8:32 &#8212; &#8220;spare&#8221; = held back = withheld). What God asks Abraham to give, and what Abraham gives willingly, God gives for real in the gospel: the beloved Son not withheld. The stopping of the sacrifice in v12 is the type&#8217;s limit; in Christ, the Father does not stop.</p>",
"13": "<p>Abraham looked up and saw a ram caught by its horns in a thicket; he went and took the ram and sacrificed it as a burnt offering instead of his son &#8212; the ram as the substitutionary sacrifice. The ram dies in the place of Isaac: this is the OT&#8217;s clearest picture of substitutionary atonement. Christ is the ultimate substitute: &#8220;He himself bore our sins in his body on the cross&#8221; (1 Pet 2:24); &#8220;Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us&#8221; (Gal 3:13); &#8220;God made him who had no sin to be sin for us&#8221; (2 Cor 5:21). The ram caught in the thicket &#8212; thorns on its head &#8212; is an image the tradition has long connected to Christ wearing a crown of thorns (John 19:2), the substitute bearing the sign of the curse in place of the sinner.</p>",
"14": "<p>Abraham called that place &#8220;The LORD Will Provide&#8221; (YHWH-Jireh). &#8220;On the mountain of the LORD it will be provided&#8221; &#8212; the naming of Moriah as the place of divine provision is a covenant name that carries forward: &#8220;on the mountain of the LORD it will be provided.&#8221; The future passive (&#8220;it will be provided&#8221;) is both a name-etiology and a prophecy: the provision is not exhausted by the ram but points to a future provision on the same mountain. 2 Chronicles 3:1 identifies Moriah as the site of Solomon&#8217;s temple in Jerusalem &#8212; and Jerusalem is where Christ was crucified. On the mountain of the LORD, the ultimate provision is indeed provided: the Lamb of God who takes away the sin of the world. YHWH-Jireh is fulfilled at Golgotha.</p>",
"15": "<p>The angel of the LORD called to Abraham from heaven a second time &#8212; the second calling signals a new, heightened covenant declaration following the test. The double call from heaven corresponds to the double witness pattern of OT law (Deut 19:15: &#8220;a matter must be established by the testimony of two or three witnesses&#8221;). The second calling introduces the covenant oath of vv16&#8211;18, which is the most solemn renewal of the Abrahamic promise in the narrative. Heb 6:17&#8211;18 uses this oath to assure believers: &#8220;God wanted to make the unchanging nature of his purpose very clear&#8230; by two unchangeable things in which it is impossible for God to lie.&#8221;</p>",
"16": "<p>&#8220;I swear by myself, declares the LORD, that because you have done this and have not withheld your son, your only son&#8221; &#8212; God swears by himself because there is no greater oath-giver. Heb 6:13: &#8220;When God made his promise to Abraham, since there was no one greater for him to swear by, he swore by himself.&#8221; The divine self-oath establishes the absolute security of the promise. The oath is a response to Abraham&#8217;s obedience &#8212; not that Abraham earned the promise, but that his faithfulness is the occasion for the solemn covenant renewal. Paul in Romans 4 is careful to show that the oath-based covenant is prior to and independent of the law, so that it comes &#8220;by faith&#8230; in order that it may be by grace&#8221; (Rom 4:16).</p>",
"17": "<p>&#8220;I will surely bless you and make your descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and as the sand on the seashore. Your descendants will take possession of the cities of their enemies&#8221; &#8212; the dual promise: innumerable offspring and military victory. Paul in Gal 3:29 identifies the believers in Christ as the fulfillment of the innumerable-offspring promise: &#8220;If you belong to Christ, then you are Abraham&#8217;s seed, and heirs according to the promise.&#8221; The &#8220;taking possession of the cities of their enemies&#8221; finds its spiritual fulfillment in Christ&#8217;s declaration: &#8220;the gates of Hades will not overcome&#8221; the church he builds (Matt 16:18). The military victory over enemies is fulfilled in Christ&#8217;s conquest of sin, death, and the devil (Col 2:15).</p>",
"18": "<p>&#8220;Through your offspring all nations on earth will be blessed, because you have obeyed me&#8221; &#8212; the universal blessing through Abraham&#8217;s offspring. Paul quotes this in Gal 3:8 as the gospel announced in advance: &#8220;the Scripture foresaw that God would justify the Gentiles by faith, and announced the gospel in advance to Abraham: &#8216;All nations will be blessed through you.&#8217;&#8221; The &#8220;offspring&#8221; through whom all nations are blessed is identified by Paul in Gal 3:16 as Christ. The mission of the church to all nations (Matt 28:19) is the outworking of this promise: through Christ, Abraham&#8217;s single offspring, the Akedah-born blessing flows to every nation, tribe, people, and language (Rev 7:9).</p>",
"19": "<p>Abraham returned to his servants, and they set off together for Beersheba. And Abraham stayed in Beersheba &#8212; the return after the sacrifice and the covenant renewal. The return &#8212; with Isaac &#8212; is itself the type-fulfillment that Heb 11:19 notes: Abraham &#8220;received Isaac back from the dead.&#8221; After the Akedah, Isaac is alive where he might have been dead; after the cross, Christ is alive where death expected him to stay dead. Both returns are to the same community (the servants; the disciples), both are unexpected reversals of the logic of sacrifice, both inaugurate a new phase of covenant life. The return to Beersheba after Moriah is the type of the return to Galilee (Matt 28:10) after Golgotha.</p>",
"20": "<p>After these things Abraham was told that Milcah had borne sons to his brother Nahor &#8212; the genealogical report that introduces Rebekah&#8217;s family (v23: Bethuel became the father of Rebekah). The narrative pivot from the Akedah to the genealogy is unexpected but purposeful: immediately after the most intense test of the covenant promise, the narrative provides the next step toward its fulfillment. Rebekah will become Isaac&#8217;s wife (ch24), continuing the covenant line. The genealogy after the Akedah is the narrative&#8217;s way of saying: the covenant continues; the sacrifice does not end the story. After the cross, the genealogy of the church (Acts 2&#8211;28) is the continuation that the death could not stop.</p>",
"21": "<p>Uz the firstborn and Buz his brother &#8212; Nahor&#8217;s sons. Uz is the home of Job (Job 1:1); Buz is the origin of Elihu (Job 32:2). The narrative&#8217;s genealogical lists connect figures across the canon: Job&#8217;s suffering and questioning connects the patriarchal era to the wisdom literature&#8217;s wrestling with God. Job&#8217;s anticipation of a mediator-redeemer (Job 9:33: &#8220;if only there were someone to mediate between us&#8221;; 19:25: &#8220;I know that my redeemer lives&#8221;) is one of the OT&#8217;s most explicit longings for Christ as the advocate who stands between the suffering human and the holy God. The Uz connection places Job within the Abrahamic family network.</p>",
"22": "<p>Kesed, Hazo, Pildash, Jidlaph, and Bethuel &#8212; the remaining sons of Nahor by Milcah. These names are otherwise unrecorded in Scripture except as ancestors. The genealogy is the canonical-context note that situates the covenant family in its extended network of relationships. All the genealogical lists in Genesis are steps in the narrowing path from Adam to Noah to Shem to Abraham to Isaac to Jacob to Judah to David to Christ (Matt 1:1&#8211;17; Luke 3:23&#8211;38). The names that do not appear in the direct covenant line are still part of the providential landscape through which Christ&#8217;s lineage is preserved and prepared.</p>",
"23": "<p>Bethuel became the father of Rebekah. Milcah bore these eight sons to Abraham&#8217;s brother Nahor &#8212; the key genealogical information: Rebekah is introduced. Rebekah will be Isaac&#8217;s wife (24:67), the mother of Jacob and Esau, and the next woman through whom the covenant promise is passed. Paul in Rom 9:10&#8211;12 uses Rebekah&#8217;s pregnancy as the key example of election by grace: &#8220;Yet, before the twins were born or had done anything good or bad &#8212; in order that God&#8217;s purpose in election might stand: not by works but by him who calls &#8212; she was told, &#8216;The older will serve the younger.&#8217;&#8221; Rebekah&#8217;s introduction here is the genealogical step that leads to Jacob, then to the twelve tribes, then to Judah, then to David, then to Christ.</p>",
"24": "<p>His concubine Reumah also had sons: Tebah, Gaham, Tahash, and Maakah &#8212; Nahor&#8217;s sons by his concubine. The secondary line through the concubine &#8212; parallel to the Hagar/Ishmael situation &#8212; is a canonical-context note showing that the covenant promise runs through specific primary lines, not through all descendants equally. The narrowing of the covenant from all Noah&#8217;s descendants to Shem, from Shem to Abraham, from Abraham to Isaac, from Isaac to Jacob, and ultimately to the one seed who is Christ (Gal 3:16) proceeds by divine election and promise, not by natural birth order or status. The concubine&#8217;s sons are part of the world through which the covenant moves, not the channel through which it flows.</p>",
},
"23": {
"1": "<p>Sarah lived to be a hundred and twenty-seven years old &#8212; the only woman in the OT whose age at death is recorded. Sarah&#8217;s age is given as a mark of honor and covenant significance: she is not merely an appendage to Abraham but a covenant figure in her own right (17:15&#8211;16: &#8220;I will bless her&#8230; she will be the mother of nations&#8221;). Paul identifies Sarah as the covenant-matriarch whose free-woman status defines the gospel community (Gal 4:26: &#8220;the Jerusalem that is above is free, and she is our mother&#8221;; 4:31: &#8220;we are not children of the slave woman, but of the free woman&#8221;). 1 Pet 3:6 holds Sarah up as the model of holy wifely faith. Her death at 127 closes the chapter of the promise-generation.</p>",
"2": "<p>Sarah died at Kiriath Arba (Hebron) in Canaan, and Abraham went to mourn for Sarah and to weep over her &#8212; the first death of a major covenant figure in the narrative. Abraham&#8217;s mourning is grief within faith: he mourns Sarah&#8217;s death while holding the promise that was given through her. The NT pattern of grief within hope: &#8220;Brothers and sisters, we do not want you to be uninformed about those who sleep in death, so that you do not grieve like the rest of mankind, who have no hope&#8221; (1 Thess 4:13). The grief is real; the hope transforms it. Christ himself weeps at Lazarus&#8217; tomb (John 11:35) before raising him &#8212; the tears of genuine grief from the one who is &#8220;the resurrection and the life&#8221; (John 11:25).</p>",
"3": "<p>Abraham rose from beside his dead wife and spoke to the Hittites &#8212; the rising from mourning to act on behalf of the dead is the covenant-faithful response. Abraham&#8217;s rising to secure burial for Sarah is an act of faith in the future: he is buying land in a country that God has promised to give him. The purchase of Machpelah is a down payment on the promised inheritance, an act of faith that the promise is real even though it has not been fully realized. Faith acts in the present on the basis of the future promise; this is the pattern of the Christian life (Heb 11:1: &#8220;faith is confidence in what we hope for and assurance about what we do not see&#8221;).</p>",
"4": "<p>&#8220;I am a foreigner and stranger among you. Sell me some property for a burial site here so I can bury my dead&#8221; &#8212; &#8220;foreigner and stranger&#8221; (ger and toshav) is the self-description that Hebrews 11:13 makes paradigmatic for all people of faith: &#8220;they admitted that they were foreigners and strangers on earth.&#8221; 1 Pet 2:11: &#8220;Dear friends, I urge you, as foreigners and exiles, to abstain from sinful desires.&#8221; The pilgrim identity that Abraham voices before the Hittites is the identity of all who live &#8220;by faith, not by sight&#8221; (2 Cor 5:7), looking for the city whose architect and builder is God (Heb 11:10). Christ himself had no permanent earthly home (Luke 9:58) and calls his followers into the same pilgrim posture.</p>",
"5": "<p>The Hittites replied to Abraham &#8212; the Gentile community&#8217;s respectful response to the covenant-bearer is a type of the openness to Abraham&#8217;s greater descendant. The Hittites treat Abraham as &#8220;a mighty prince among us&#8221; (v6) despite his self-description as a foreigner. The recognition of the covenant-bearer&#8217;s dignity by the surrounding peoples anticipates the eschatological recognition of Christ&#8217;s lordship: &#8220;at the name of Jesus every knee should bow&#8230; and every tongue acknowledge that Jesus Christ is Lord&#8221; (Phil 2:10&#8211;11). The willing deference of the Hittites is the small-scale type of the universal acknowledgment that Christ&#8217;s lordship will one day receive.</p>",
"6": "<p>&#8220;Sir, listen to us. You are a mighty prince among us. Bury your dead in the choicest of our tombs&#8221; &#8212; Abraham is recognized as a &#8220;mighty prince&#8221; (lit. &#8220;prince of God&#8221; &#8212; nesi&#8217; elohim) by the Hittites. The recognition of Abraham&#8217;s royal-divine status by the Gentile community is a type of the recognition of Christ as the &#8220;King of kings and Lord of lords&#8221; (Rev 19:16) that will come from all peoples. Christ is not merely a prince of God but God the Son (John 1:1; Phil 2:6); the Hittites&#8217; recognition of Abraham as God&#8217;s prince is the type of the universal recognition that Christ&#8217;s lordship will receive from every nation.</p>",
"7": "<p>Abraham rose and bowed down before the people of the land, the Hittites &#8212; the humble posture of the covenant-bearer before the Gentile community. Abraham&#8217;s bowing in cultural respect is not compromise but courtesy &#8212; the proper negotiating posture in the ANE. Christ engages similarly with all people, accepting hospitality from those outside the covenant (Luke 7:36: dining with the Pharisee; Luke 19:5: entering Zacchaeus&#8217;s home). The covenant-bearer&#8217;s humble engagement with the surrounding culture is the model for the church&#8217;s missionary posture: &#8220;becoming all things to all people&#8221; (1 Cor 9:22) without compromising the covenant identity.</p>",
"8": "<p>Abraham said, &#8220;If you are willing to let me bury my dead, then intercede with Ephron son of Zohar on my behalf&#8221; &#8212; Abraham seeks an intermediary to approach Ephron. The use of community elders as intermediaries in land transactions is the ANE legal norm. The use of intermediaries runs through the OT: Moses as mediator of the Sinai covenant, priests as mediators of worship, prophets as mediators of the divine word. Christ is the mediator who replaces all these: &#8220;there is one God and one mediator between God and mankind, the man Christ Jesus&#8221; (1 Tim 2:5). The chain of intermediaries in the OT points toward and is superseded by the one Mediator of the new covenant.</p>",
"9": "<p>&#8220;Ask him to sell me the cave of Machpelah, which belongs to him and is at the end of his field. Ask him to sell it to me at the full price as a burial site among you&#8221; &#8212; Abraham asks to pay full price, not to receive a gift. The insistence on paying the full price for the burial site corresponds to the gospel&#8217;s insistence that the full price of sin has been paid: &#8220;You are not your own; you were bought at a price&#8221; (1 Cor 6:19&#8211;20); &#8220;the precious blood of Christ, a lamb without blemish or defect&#8221; (1 Pet 1:19). Abraham&#8217;s full-price purchase is a type of the full payment of atonement: nothing partial, nothing subsidized by the seller, but the complete transaction that secures permanent ownership.</p>",
"10": "<p>Ephron the Hittite replied to Abraham in the hearing of all the Hittites who had come to the gate of the city &#8212; the public negotiation at the city gate is the formal legal setting of ANE property transactions. The city gate is the site of legal proceedings throughout the OT: Boaz redeems Ruth at the gate of Bethlehem (Ruth 4:1&#8211;11); the elders judge at the gate (Deut 21:19; 22:15). The public legal nature of Abraham&#8217;s purchase gives it binding legal permanence. The new covenant is similarly made publicly: &#8220;This is what has been publicly declared: God has made Jesus both Lord and Messiah, this Jesus whom you crucified&#8221; (Acts 2:36). The covenant is a public legal transaction, not a private arrangement.</p>",
"11": "<p>&#8220;No, my lord, listen to me; I give you the field, and I give you the cave that is in it. I give it to you in the presence of my people. Bury your dead&#8221; &#8212; Ephron&#8217;s initial offer of a gift rather than a sale. In ANE negotiating custom, offering to give is the first move in a negotiation that will conclude with payment. Abraham insists on paying (v12&#8211;13) because he will not be indebted to the Hittites for his covenant landholding &#8212; the same principle as his refusal of the king of Sodom&#8217;s offer (14:23). The covenant inheritance cannot be received as a gift from those outside the covenant; it must be purchased through the covenant mediator. The new covenant inheritance is purchased by Christ, not given by the world.</p>",
"12": "<p>Abraham bowed down before the people of the land &#8212; the repeated gesture of respect in the negotiation. The humble persistence of covenant-seeking in a transactional world is the pattern of prayer: &#8220;keep on asking&#8230; keep on seeking&#8230; keep on knocking&#8221; (Matt 7:7 &#8212; the present tense imperatives). Abraham does not accept Ephron&#8217;s first offer but persists in seeking the proper transaction. The persistence in prayer that Jesus teaches (Luke 18:1&#8211;8: the persistent widow) has its type in the patriarchal persistence in covenant-negotiation. Both persist until the proper, complete transaction is secured.</p>",
"13": "<p>Abraham said, &#8220;Listen to me, if you will. I will pay the price of the field. Accept it from me so I can bury my dead there&#8221; &#8212; the insistence on full payment. Abraham refuses the free gift because owning Canaan as a gift from the Hittites would undermine the covenant claim that God has promised to give it. The integrity of the covenant inheritance requires that it not be received on terms set by those outside the covenant. The new covenant inheritance &#8212; justification, adoption, eternal life &#8212; is similarly not given on terms set by human religious achievement or moral effort; it comes exclusively through Christ&#8217;s payment (Titus 3:5: &#8220;he saved us, not because of righteous things we had done, but because of his mercy&#8221;).</p>",
"14": "<p>Ephron answered Abraham &#8212; the negotiation continues. The formal ANE negotiating pattern &#8212; offer, counteroffer, acceptance &#8212; is preserved in the narrative detail. The patience of the covenant-bearer in working through the proper legal channels is a type of Christ&#8217;s fulfillment of every legal requirement: &#8220;Let it be so now; it is proper for us to do this to fulfill all righteousness&#8221; (Matt 3:15 &#8212; Christ submitting to baptism to fulfill the law&#8217;s requirements). Every proper form is honored; no legal corner is cut; the covenant is secured through the proper channels.</p>",
"15": "<p>&#8220;My lord, listen to me; the land is worth four hundred shekels of silver, but what is that between you and me? Bury your dead&#8221; &#8212; Ephron names a price while appearing to minimize its significance. The four hundred shekels of silver is a substantial sum (by comparison, David pays fifty shekels for the threshing floor in 2 Sam 24:24; Joseph is sold for twenty shekels in Gen 37:28). The seemingly casual &#8220;what is that between you and me?&#8221; is the ANE politeness that masks the serious transaction. The full weight of the price &#8212; however minimized in language &#8212; must be paid. The full price of human sin, however minimized in human estimation, must be paid; Christ pays it in full (John 19:30: &#8220;It is finished&#8221; = the debt is paid).</p>",
"16": "<p>Abraham agreed and weighed out four hundred shekels of silver according to the weight current among the merchants &#8212; the full price paid in silver, publicly, according to the standard of the marketplace. The payment at the current market rate using the merchants&#8217; standard ensures that the transaction is binding by any external standard. The atonement Christ provides is similarly calibrated to the full standard of divine justice: &#8220;The wages of sin is death&#8221; (Rom 6:23); Christ pays the full wage. The ransom paid for many (Matt 20:28) is not a negotiated discount but the full market rate of divine holiness satisfied by the one sacrifice of infinite worth.</p>",
"17": "<p>Ephron&#8217;s field in Machpelah near Mamre &#8212; both the field and the cave, and all the trees within the borders &#8212; was deeded to Abraham as his property &#8212; the comprehensive legal description of what was purchased. The specific, legally precise description &#8212; field, cave, trees, borders &#8212; ensures that the covenant possession is exactly defined and legally unambiguous. The inheritance secured by Christ is similarly precisely defined in the NT: &#8220;an inheritance that can never perish, spoil or fade &#8212; kept in heaven for you&#8221; (1 Pet 1:4). The covenant inheritance is not vague but specific; not provisional but permanent; not conditional on human faithfulness but secured by Christ&#8217;s once-for-all purchase.</p>",
"18": "<p>The field was deeded to Abraham as his property in the presence of all the Hittites who had come to the gate of the city &#8212; the public legal ratification. The full community witnesses the transfer of ownership; the covenant possession is secured by public witness, not private agreement. The public dimension of the atonement &#8212; the crucifixion done in public view, the resurrection announced publicly, the gospel proclaimed to all nations &#8212; is the new covenant&#8217;s public ratification. &#8220;God presented Christ as a sacrifice of atonement&#8230; to demonstrate his righteousness&#8221; (Rom 3:25) &#8212; the atonement is a public demonstration, not a private transaction between God and a few.</p>",
"19": "<p>Abraham buried his wife Sarah in the cave in the field of Machpelah near Mamre (Hebron) in the land of Canaan &#8212; the burial of the covenant-matriarch in the promised land. Sarah is the first to be buried in Machpelah; she will be followed by Abraham (25:9&#8211;10), Isaac and Rebekah (49:31), Leah (49:31), and Jacob (50:13). The cave becomes the covenant family&#8217;s tomb. The tomb in the promised land is a statement of faith: the covenant family plants its dead in the land of promise, trusting the resurrection. Heb 11:13 says they &#8220;were still living by faith when they died&#8221; &#8212; dying in the promised land rather than returning to Ur. The tomb in Canaan is the type of Christ&#8217;s tomb in Jerusalem: the death planted in the promised city from which resurrection life emerges.</p>",
"20": "<p>So the field and the cave were deeded to Abraham by the Hittites as a burial site &#8212; the chapter closes with the legal completion. The first permanent possession of the promised land is a burial site &#8212; a place for the dead, not the living. This is the covenant-faith inversion: the first foothold in the land of promise is claimed through death. Christ&#8217;s first permanent mark on history is also through death: the cross planted on Golgotha, the tomb sealed in the garden. But the burial site is never the final word: Isaac&#8217;s family buries their dead in Machpelah while trusting the resurrection; Christ&#8217;s tomb is emptied on the third day. The cave at Machpelah is the type of the empty tomb: death entered in faith, and the stone that seals it does not have the final word.</p>",
},
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW_DATA)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'genesis', existing)
    print('Genesis 20-23 mkt-christ written.')

